{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619899"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16596"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16596"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.03,0.07,0.01,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66951"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9287"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52405"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5011"},{"type":"tags","id":"5323"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22388"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66951"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAspirin is a commonly used medication with several indications ranging from pain relief to prevention of cardiovascular events.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the drug\u0027s primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Competitive inhibition of thromboxane synthesis","Reversible blockade of arachidonic acid release","Direct inhibition of platelet aggregation","Reversible binding to prostaglandin receptors","Irreversible inhibition of cyclooxygenase enzymes"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAspirin works through \u003Cstrong\u003Eirreversible inhibition of cyclooxygenase enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E by acetylating a serine residue in the enzyme\u0027s active site. This prevents the conversion of arachidonic acid to prostaglandins and thromboxanes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReversible binding to prostaglandin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: aspirin does not act at prostaglandin receptors but prevents prostaglandin synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitive inhibition of thromboxane synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: the inhibition is irreversible, not competitive, and occurs at cyclooxygenase rather than directly affecting thromboxane synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspirin works through reduction of thromboxane synthesis; it does not cause \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect inhibition of platelet aggregation. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReversible blockade of arachidonic acid release\u003C/strong\u003E: aspirin does not affect arachidonic acid release from membrane phospholipids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe irreversible nature of aspirin\u0027s action is particularly important for its antiplatelet effects, as platelets cannot synthesize new cyclooxygenase enzymes. This results in prolonged antiplatelet effects that persist for the platelet\u0027s lifespan (7-10 days).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aspirin irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase enzymes by acetylating a serine residue.","Cyclooxygenase inhibition reduces prostaglandin and thromboxane synthesis.","Low-dose aspirin primarily affects platelets due to their inability to synthesize new cyclooxygenase enzymes."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52405"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16596"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52405"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T08:35:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T08:36:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9287"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66951"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifyin